Claims Claims 1. A process for purification of a feed gas comprising the steps of: - compressing the feed gas; - removing water from the compressed gas; treating the at least partially dried and compressed gas for the removal of imparities, Wherein the treatment step comprises passing the at least partially dried and compressed gas through a solvent absorber to remove volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and carbon dioxide and any water , wherein the solvent absorber is arranged in a solvent circulation circuit comprising a first and a second treatment means for regeneration of the solvent to remove the absorbed impurities, said first treatment means being configured for operating at a higher pressure than the second treatment means, and wherein part of the solvent is divided from the solvent recirculation circuit in a removal stream, which division occurs in or downstream of the first treatment means and upstream of the second treatment means, which removal stream is after reduction of its VOC concentration returned to the solvent recirculation circuit. 2. The process of claim 1 , wherein up to 10volume% of the solvent in the solvent recirculation circuit is divided into the removal stream, preferably up to 5%, more preferably 0.5 to 2% by volume. 3. The process of claim 1 or 2, wherein the treated gas is further passed through a membrane unit downstream of the solvent absorber to reduce the carbon dioxide content of the gas to obtain purified gas. 4. The process as claimed in claim 1 or 2 or 3, wherein the treated gas is partially recirculated to the compressor, wherein a recirculation ratio is less than 1.3, wherein the recirculation ratio is defined as the ratio of gas flow after compression and feed gas flow before compression. 5. The process as claimed in claim 4, wherein the recirculation ratio is less than. 1.2. 6. The process as claimed in any of the preceding claims, wherein the solvent absorber is operated at a temperature in the range of 0 to 10Â°C. 7. The process as claimed in claim 1 -6, wherein the reduction of the VOC content in the removal stream comprises the step of stripping the solvent by means of a strip gas, wherein the treatment in the first and the second treatment means particularly comprises a pressure reduction configured to generate flash gas. 8. The process as claimed in Claim 7, wherein the reduction of the VOC content in the removal stream is carried out according to the method as claimed in any of the claims 15- 19. 9, The process as claimed in claim 7-8, wherein the strip gas is flash gas coming from the first treatment means in the solvent recirculation circuit 10. The process as claimed in claim 7-9, wherein the solvent stream is added to the solvent recirculation circuit in the second treatment means. 11. The process as claimed in any of the preceding claims, wherein carbon dioxide is liberated in the regeneration of the solvent hi the second treatment means. 12. The process as claimed in claim 11, wherein the resulting carbon dioxide stream is scrubbed with the solvent stream prior to its addition to the solvent recirculation circuit. 13. The process as claimed in any of the preceding claims, wherein the feed gas is chosen from biogas, landfill gas and/or natural gas, and wherein hydrogen sulphide has bees removed from the feed gas prior to compression. 14. The process as claimed in any of the preceding claims, wherein the at least partially dried and compressed gas is contacted in the solvent absorber with a solvent in a substantially isothermal manner. 15. A method for the separation of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) from a feed stream comprising a solvent, wherein use is made of a condensation circuit comprising a scrubber, a stripper, a cooler and a vapour-liquid separator, comprising the steps of; Scrubbing a recirculation gas stream from the vapour-liquid separator with the feed stream in the scrubber; - Stripping the feed stream in the stripper with a strip gas to obtain a solvent stream and a gas stream enriched in VOCs; 

 - Condensing at least part of the VOCs present in the gas stream enriched in VOCs in the cooler; Separating condensed VOCs into an outlet stream, wherein remaining gas is at least partially recirculated as the recirculation gas stream to the scrubber. 16. The method as claimed in claim 15, wherein the solvent stream is heat exchanged with me feed stream in a heat exchanger downstream of the scrubber, 17. The method as claimed in claim 15 or 16, wherein part of the outlet stream of condensed VOCs is recirculated to the stripper. 18. The method as claimed in any of the claims 15-17, wherein the gas stream enriched in VOCs is cooled downstream of the stripper to a temperature below 10Â°Q preferably below 5Â°C. 19. The method as claimed in any of the claims 15-18, wherein the feed stream further comprises water, and wherein at least part of the water is condensed is the condensing step and then separated into a second aqueous outlet stream. 20. A system for the purification of feed gas comprising: - a compressor with an inlet for feed gas, an inlet for a recirculation gas stream, and an outlet for compressed gas; - Cooling means for cooling the compressed gas; - A gas-liquid separator arranged downstream of the cooling means for removal of condensate formed during treatment of the compressed gas with the cooling means; - Means for absorbing impurities including volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and carbon dioxide from the compressed and at least partially dried gas, provided with a recirculation outlet for a recirculation gas stream, and an outlet for the thus purified gas, wherein - the means for absorbing impurities comprise a solvent absorber, which is provided with an. inlet for solvent, and with an outlet for the thus treated gas; the solvent absorber is arranged in a solvent circulation circuit comprising a first and a second treatment means for regeneration of the solvent to remove absorbed impurities, said first treatment means being configured for operating at a higher pressure than the second treatment means, 

 - the solvent recirculation circuit is configured for splitting off a removal stream in or downstream the first treatment means and upstream the second treatment means, - a reclaimer unit is present for reducing the VOC concentration of the removal stream, a solvent outlet of the reclaiming unit being coupled to the solvent recirculation circuit. 21. The system as claimed in claim 20, wherein the reclaimer unit comprises a stripper. 22. The system as claimed in Claim 20 or 21, wherein the reclaimer unit comprises the apparatus as claimed in any of the claims 25-27, 23. The system as claimed in any of the Claims 20-22, wherein the means for absorbing further comprise a separation unit downstream of the solvent absorber, said separation being provided with the recirculation outlet and the outlet for purified gas, which separation unit is configured for farther reducing a carbon dioxide content of the treated gas, and preferably is a membrane separation unit 24. The system as claimed in any of the Claims 14-20, wherein said solvent circulation circuit further comprises cooling means arranged downstream of said first and second cooling means to cool the solvent to a temperature substantially corresponding to a temperature of the compressed and dried gas. 25. An apparatus for the separation of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) from a feed stream, comprising a condensation circuit provided with: A scrubber comprising an inlet for the feed stream comprising a solvent with VOCs and an outlet for the feed stream enriched in VOCs, an inlet for a recirculated gas stream, an outlet for a scrubbed gas stream; - A stripper arranged downstream of the solvent scrubber, with an inlet for ship gas, an inlet for the feed stream, an gas outlet for a gas stream enriched in VOCs and an outlet for a solvent stream; ~ A cooler arranged downstream of the stripper and configured for cooling the gas stream; - A vapour-liquid separator coupled to the cooler, and having an. outlet for a liquid stream and a recirculation outlet for a gas stream, wherein said gas stream from the recirculation outlet is at least partially recirculated to the scrubber. 26. The apparatus as claimed in Claim 25, farther comprising a heat exchanger for heat exchange between the feed stream downstream of the scrubber and the solvent stream. 27. The apparatus as claimed in Claim 25 or 26, wherein the vapour-liquid separator is a three- phase separator with a first outlet for a liquid stream primarily or substantially consisting of VOCs, a second outlet for an aqueous liquid stream and the recirculation outlet.
